<span id="freeTextContainer17670449819951668235">“We have doomed the wolf not for what it is, but for what we deliberately and mistakenly perceive it to be...”<br/><br/>Mowat, a naturalist/biologist is given an assignment: spend the summer in the subarctic and study wolf behavior, particularly, their feeding habits. Mowat discovers one wolf family and follows them closely, for several months. It is an eye-opening experience, giving him a deeper understanding and compassion for this misunderstood animal.<br/><br/>This is a terrific read. Funny and adventurous. I h</span>
  <span id="freeText17670449819951668235" style="display:none">“We have doomed the wolf not for what it is, but for what we deliberately and mistakenly perceive it to be...”<br /><br />Mowat, a naturalist/biologist is given an assignment: spend the summer in the subarctic and study wolf behavior, particularly, their feeding habits. Mowat discovers one wolf family and follows them closely, for several months. It is an eye-opening experience, giving him a deeper understanding and compassion for this misunderstood animal.<br /><br />This is a terrific read. Funny and adventurous. I have heard much of it is fictionalized, but as a story, it really resounds. Surprisingly, it was written, about 50 years ago but still remains fresh and entertaining.<br /></span>
