    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1643661497" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1643661497" />
    <a title="Evelyn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3592873-evelyn"><img alt="Evelyn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1604198633p2/3592873.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1643661497?book_show_action=true">May 20, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Evelyn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Evelyn" href="/user/show/3592873-evelyn">Evelyn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer1643661497&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1643661497" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3707966162449482715">This was my second time around reading Never Cry Wolf and, just as he did the first time, Mowat delights. The first half of the novel is a series of comedic misadventures, Mowat portraying himself as a well-meaning but meek and somewhat bumbling biologist, never quite certain what he&apos;s gotten himself into and yet always game for a good experiment. After some not insignificant difficulties, Mowat finds a family of wolves which he studies over the course of several months. The wolves act mostly di</span>
  <span id="freeText3707966162449482715" style="display:none">This was my second time around reading Never Cry Wolf and, just as he did the first time, Mowat delights. The first half of the novel is a series of comedic misadventures, Mowat portraying himself as a well-meaning but meek and somewhat bumbling biologist, never quite certain what he's gotten himself into and yet always game for a good experiment. After some not insignificant difficulties, Mowat finds a family of wolves which he studies over the course of several months. The wolves act mostly disinterested towards him, something that surprises him but nonetheless he takes in stride, and through his observations Mowat learns both about wolves and also himself. There's lots of humour in this part of the book - my favourite moments include the radio message sent to Mowat from Ottawa, and Mowat observing the empty wolf den over the esker for hours, standing up to pee, and seeing all three wolves standing behind him observing him. <br /><br />The novel takes a grim turn during the second half. Mowat relates a few stories about wolf hunting. A particularly emotionally straining one is the story he tells about a wolf who contracted rabies, and was hunted mercilessly by the residents of Churchill. Mowat goes on the explain the reality of rabies in animals - it results in a loss of any sense of protection and fear, and so animals wander directly into towns as with this particular wolf. This is not the only emotionally taxing story Mowat tells in this portion of the book. The hunters' mass slaughter of caribou is hard to read as well. <br /><br />No doubt there is a lot of controversy as to Mowat's truthfulness. I didn't know about this controversy the first time I read the book, but was aware this time around. I don't know where exactly I stand on the issue. I've got a few feelings about it that I don't necessarily want to get into right now. But I think there's no doubt that Mowat knows how to tell a story. He can make you laugh, startle you, and force a fair amount of introspection. His bluntness is his greatest strength, and he refuses to shy away from things that are scary or uncomfortable. This book is funny, painful, and an important read for anyone interested in nature and animals.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3707966162449482715" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

